Directions:
From Kremmling, get on I-70 W in Eagle County from Co Rd 1, County Rd 1 and CO-131 S

1 h 1 min (41.3 mi) 

 Follow I-70 W to I-70BL W/US-6 W in Clifton. Take exit 37 from I-70 W

1 h 45 min (121 mi)

 Follow CO-141 S/32 Rd to Divide Rd, Follow divide road SE to the Dominguez Campground.

From the campground take the Tabeguache trail S for about 2 miles. 

At the fork head E up the canyon into Dominguez-Escalante, (D&E) followthe raod for about 4 miles.

Pass Wagon Park and head N onto the Primitive road that connects to Long Mesa rd. 

Follow Long Mesa for another 4 miles and you will arrive near the plot.
WildlifeUse: Ungulate trail and droppings in plot
OffsiteInfluences: none visible

Directions: From Grand Junction, CO take Hwy 50 southeast. Turn left on Hwy 141 and drive west. Then turn left on Road 630 which will run into road 19.50 (road p12). At about 1 mile form plot turn right on a two track and follow until 0.2 miles away from plot center.

Directions: From Grand Junction, CO take Hwy 50 Southeast then turn right onto Hwy 141. Drive past Gateway, CO. Take a left at Road P12. At around 3 miles turn left onto a two track.  Drive up a steep rocky road that looks like a boulder is in the center of the road. Reach a wildlife gate and drive through it up steep incline and narrow switch backs to the top of the Mesa. Turn left left a small two track .3 miles away from plot center.

Directions: From Clifton CO, take road 32 south to Hwy 50. Turn left on Hwy 50 going southeast. Turn left at Kannah Creek road heading east. Parked alonng  Kannah Creek road. Then hiked 0.8 miles up a draw then up a steep slope to plot center.
ParentMaterial: Residuum weathered from sandstone and shale
WildlifeUse: Elk scat present, but all older(last fall); Coyote Scat

Directions: From I-70, take the Clifton exit. Take a left onto 32 Road (Highway 141). The road will come to a T, take a left to go towards Whitewater. The plot can be accessed from a Department of Energy road on the left. You will want to let the DOE know that you will be in the area.
ParentMaterial: Colluvium derived from basalt alluvium (See Notes)
WildlifeUse: Prarie dogs in vicinity although not directly on plot. Soil may be too cobbly on side slope for burrowing. Lots of rabbit poop. No livestock use evident.
OffsiteInfluences: Can view Highway 50 from plot. Near Dept. of Energy development.
Comments: Plants on site were already dried and decadent from the season by the time sampled. Transect 3 goes down side of hill. T1 & T2 are on the ridge and shoulder.

Directions: From Gateway, Colorado, head south on Highway 141. After milemarker 86, take a left onto P12 road. Continue onto 12.8 Road. Continue onto 19 1/2 Road. Turn left onto BLM 7400 and follow this road to plot. When we visited, there were large boulders in the road that prevented our truck from travelling very far along it. You may want to take a UTV.
ParentMaterial: Residuum from interbedded sandstone and shale
WildlifeUse: Two Juniper titmice on plot. Flock of swallows. Rabbit poop, elk and deer poop. Numerous very dried out cow pies. Cow/game trail near T3.
ManagementHistory: Grazing Allotment: Blue Mesa; Pasture 3. Gunnison Sage Grouse Historic Range.
OffsiteInfluences: Rarely used 2 track road within 200 ft. of plot.
Comments: Leaf litter deposited under trees and shrubs, but little litter in interspaces.

Directions: Long dirt road to DD19 Road, turned onto road towards plot, simple hike to plot. From 141, turn L onto 25R Rd, then take an immediat right to stay on 25R Rd. Turn L onto CoRd U29. Turn R on 18Y Rd. Continue on Dd19Rd. Use GPS to navigate to the plot.
WildlifeUse: Ungulate scat and horned lizards, evidence of cattle
ManagementHistory: pinyon juniper was clearly chained leaving sagebrush
OffsiteInfluences: roads 120m west and transmission lines in sight
Comments: AGCR
ESD_Investigators: Madison Morales; Meredith Talbert; Nathaniel Winkler

Directions: Easy walk right off the main dirt road. From 141, turn onto 25R Rd. Turn right to stay on 25R Rd. Turn left onto Country Rd U29W, which turns right and becomes U29 Rd. U29 Rd turns slightly right and becomes 18Y Rd. Use a GPS to navigate to the plot.
WildlifeUse: Deer skat, gopher holes, cicadas, baby horney toads all found within the plot. Cow patties and trampling looked as if it was from last year.
OffsiteInfluences: Maintained road 0.16 miles from plot center, mastication and chaining near plot
ESD_Investigators: Meredith Talbert; Madison Morales; Nathaniel Winkler

Directions: Not far off road, easy hike. From 141, turn onto 25R Rd. Turn left onto CoRd U29 W. From here use maps and GPS to navigate to plot.
WildlifeUse: Deer skat, saw a yellow collard lizard, and many ant hills. Cow patties are old and the grazing looks like it had been from last year. An old water troft was seen <.25 miles from plot center.
OffsiteInfluences: Large wash 200 yards away from plot center, a cattle trail intersected T1.
ESD_Investigators: Madison Morales; Meredith Talbert; Nathaniel Winkler

Directions: Quick 4wd road through private, easy hike. From 141, turn onto 25R Rd. Follow 25R Rd, County Rd U29 W and U29 Rd to W Fork Dry Creek. Use maps and GPS to nagivate to the plot.
WildlifeUse: ungulate scat and cattle evidence
OffsiteInfluences: road .25 mile away, pinyon/juniper mastication near, possible chaining around plot
Comments: small grainage running through plot about 1 meter wide
ESD_Investigators: Madison Morales; Meredith Talbert; Nathaniel Winkler

Directions: Tight 4wd pipeline road, easy hike along game trails. From 141, tun onto 25R rd. Continue on 25R Rd, then take U29 Rd to JJ 19 Rd. Use maps and GPS to navigate to plot.
WildlifeUse: Bear tracks and scat found less than 100m from plot center (not fresh but from this year), fox or coyote den near T2 , ungulate scat and many game trails. No evidence of recent cattle grazing (within 1 year +) usuage. No browsed grasses/scat.
OffsiteInfluences: Road about 100m from plot.
ESD_Investigators: Madison Morales; Meredith Talbert; Nathaniel Winkler

Directions: Extremely long and rough road through Utah into Greasewood Canyon and Coyote Wash, UTV recommended, hiked into Colorado down wash to plot. From 491, drive into Utah. Turn R onto W Summit Rd, Continue onto Ucolo Rd. Continue onto Uncola Rd. Continue onto Bryan Rd/CR 370. Turn L onto Lisbon Valley Rd. Turn Right onto E Lisbon Valley Rd. Continue straight onto Island Mesa Rd. From here, good luck! Use GPS and maps to navigate to the plot. The road from here is very rough. It took us 4 hours to drive from Cortez to the hiking point to the plot down this road. Good news: once you get down this road, the area is beautiful! There is an old cowboy cabin in the area with a spring, and the hike to the plot is beautiful.
WildlifeUse: Rabbit and toad seen in the wash, bear scat, and evidence of ungulate usage. Cow patties heavy within plot, many cow trails, recent usage.
OffsiteInfluences: Wash <75m from plot center
ESD_Investigators: Meredith Talbert; Nathaniel Winkler; Madison Morales

Directions: Longer 4wd road, easy hike. From 141, turn onto 25R rd. Stay on 25R until CoRd U29 W. Turn left. From here use maps and a GPS to navigate to plot.
WildlifeUse: Ungulate skat present in the plot. Old cow patties and cattle trails were also present in the plot however there was not an abundance of sign.
OffsiteInfluences: Dirt road less than .25 miles from plot center
ESD_Investigators: Madison Morales; Meredith Talbert; Nathaniel Winkler
